definition.value: Mosaicism involving a particular cell or cells.
Mosaicism involving a particular chromosome or chromosomes.
Mosaicism involving a particular gene or genes.
A type of genetic mosaicism where more than one set of genetic information is found specifically within the gamete cells.

The presence of genetically distinct populations of somatic cells in a given organism caused by DNA mutations, epigenetic alterations of DNA, chromosomal conditions or the spontaneous reversion of inherited mutations.
Mosaicism involving the allosome.
Mosaicism involving the autosome.
A genetic mosaic in which some cells are 45,X and others are 46,XX.
A genetic mosaic in which some cells are 45,X and others are 46,XY.
A genetic mosaic in which some cells are 46,XXY and others are 46,XX.
A genetic mosaic in which some cells are 47,XXY and others are 46,XY.
Polyploidy in which there are three sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are four sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are five sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are six sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are seven sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are eight sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are ten sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy in which there are twelve sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
Polyploidy which occurs in some tissues of animals that are otherwise diploid.
Tetraploidies observed in humans.
Triploidies observed in humans.
Human triploidy in which there are 69 sets of chromosomes per cell, including three X chromosomes.
Human tetraploidy in which there are 92 sets of chromosomes per cell in a person considered genetically female.
Human tetraploidy in which there are 92 sets of chromosomes per cell in a person considered genetically male.

A chromosomal condition in which a fetus has three copies of every chromosome instead of two. If this occurs in only some cells, it is called mosaic triploidy and is less severe. Most embryos with triploidy miscarry early in development.
Human triploidy in which there are 69 sets of chromosomes per cell, including two X chromosomes and one Y chromosome.
Human triploidy in which there are 69 sets of chromosomes per cell, including one X chromosome and two Y chromosomes.
The degree of replication of the chromosome set in the karyotype.
A chromosomal condition in which a fetus has four copies of every chromosome instead of two.
Ploidy in which there is one set of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
The chromosomal constitution of cells, in which each type of chromosome is represented twice. Symbol: 2N or 2X.
Polyploidy in which there are seven sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.
The chromosomal constitution of cells, in which each type of chromosome is represented once. Symbol: N.
Ploidy in which there are no sets of chromosomes in the cell nucleus.

A low number of circulating cells transferred from one individual to another. This often refers to fetal cells persisting in the material circulation and may play a role in the pathogenesis of autoimmune diseases.
Mosaicism occurring with brain cells.
Gain of an entire chromosome or chromosome arm.
Loss of an entire chromosome or chromosome arm.
Duplication of an entire chromosome or chromosome arm.
Variation affecting the number of chromosomes.
The condition in which one chromosome of a pair is missing. In a normally diploid cell it is represented symbolically as 2N-1.
Two copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
The condition of having additional copies of a chromosome present in a cell.
No copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
The possession of a third chromosome of any one type in an otherwise diploid cell.
Three copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
Four copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
The possession of four chromosomes of any one type in an otherwise diploid cell.
Five copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
Six copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
Seven copies of a chromosome in a cell or organism.
